==English==
===Etymology===
From the Latin ''[[evincere]]'', "to conquer entirely, to prevail over, to prove exhaustively," from ''[[e-]]'' (an intesifier) + ''[[vincere]]'', "to conquer."

===Pronunciation===
{{SAMPA|/"i.vIns/ ''or'' /"I.vIns/ ''or'' /"E.vIns/}}
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɪns|-ɪns]]

===Verb===
'''evince''' (evinced, evincing, evinces)
# (''transitive'') to [[show]] or [[demonstrate]] clearly; to [[manifest]]
#: ''Common sense and experience must and will [[evince]] the truth of this.'' - South

===Translations===
